nd":"Lavenham, Suffolk, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cooke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Cook  .","History: Francis Cooke (died 1663) and his eldest son John were passengers on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1621; they were joined two years later by Francis's wife and other children. In the words of William Bradford, he lived long enough ‘to see his children's children have children’."],"variants":[{"name":"Cook","meanings":["English: occupational name for a cook, a seller of cooked meats, or a keeper of an eating house, from Middle English <i>cok</i>, <i>coke</i>, <i>cook</i>, <i>couk</i>, <i>cuk(e)</i> (Old English <i>cōc</i>) ‘cook’ or ‘seller of cooked foods’. See also   Kew  .","Irish and Scottish: usually identical in origin with the English name (see 1 above), but in some cases a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cúg</b> ‘son of Hugo’ (see   McCook  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘cook’, such as German and Jewish   Koch  , Dutch   Kook  , Polish <b>Kucharz</b> and   Kucharczyk  , Slovenian and Croatian   Kuhar  , North German   Kuk  ."]}]},{"name":"Norman","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, from <i>nord</i> ‘north’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’, i.e. ‘Norseman’. This name was in use in England before the Conquest, and was reinforced by its use among the Norman invaders themselves. The Normans were the inhabitants of Normandy in northern France, whose name is a reference to the Vikings who took control of the region in the 9th century. In the 11th and 12th centuries they achieved remarkable conquests, including not only Britain but also Sicily, southern Italy, and Antioch. In the Scottish Highlands it is used as the Anglicized equivalent of Tormod ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Norman Cooke was born in 1360, in Suffolk, England, his father, Sir Harold Oxwell Cooke Knight II, was 15 and his mother, Lady Ena de Ross, was 13. He married Myrtle Upton in 1392. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1401, in Lavenham, Suffolk, England, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1360–1401":"1360–1401","1362–Female":"1362–Surnud","1364–Male":"1364–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1376–1425":"1376–1425","1392–1423":"1392–1423","1345–1401":"1345–1401","1347–1407":"1347–1407","1362":"1362","1361":"1361","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","1425":"1425","1347":"1347","1401":"1401","1423":"1423","1345":"1345","1376":"1376","1364":"1364","1407":"1407","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Lavenham, Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1360–1401":"1360–1401","1362–Female":"1362–Kuollut","1364–Male":"1364–Kuollut","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1376–1425":"1376–1425","1392–1423":"1392–1423","1345–1401":"1345–1401","1347–1407":"1347–1407","1362":"1362","1361":"1361","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","1425":"1425","1347":"1347","1401":"1401","1423":"1423","1345":"1345","1376":"1376","1364":"1364","1407":"1407","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Lavenham, Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England"